{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The idea that fictions may educate us is an old one, as old perhaps as the view according to which they distort the truth and mislead us.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Our aim in this chapter is to provide some clarity about what is at stake in this debate, what the options are, and how empirical work does or might bear on its resolution.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Those who think we learn from fictions do not claim that we learn from all fictions, and will probably agree that fictions are sometimes a potent source of error and ignorance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Nor is wholesale skepticism about learning from fiction-that no one ever learned anything from any fictional work-plausible; at the very least we learn about what characters and events the author has chosen to describe.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "What is likely to be questioned is a kind of easy-going optimism which takes it as obvious that exposure to the right kind of fiction (whatever that is taken to be) will give us valuable knowledge of the world and the people in it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "It is not unreasonable to ask for evidence and argument to support such a claim, and to point out that establishing that someone learned something from a particular fictional source may be rather difficult.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Learning may also involve the acquisition of skills, the refinement of our capacities, the gathering of new experiences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "These things are rarely insulated from belief change but it would be controversial to say that they are nothing more than alterations to belief.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "It is said that fictions refine our empathic abilities, make us more attuned to other perspectives, and allow us to glimpse experiences distant from our own.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "To speak of fictions as reliable sources of true beliefs may seem paradoxical, since fictions are most often thought of as trading in stories that are not true and telling us of characters that do not exist.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "However, cases of learning about the fictional work (or its maker) from the work itself are of some interest for us because they are often cases where the reliability of the source-the fiction-can be independent of the reliability of the author.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "When we consider the prospects for gaining knowledge of the world beyond the fiction, the question of the author's reliability is important, as we shall now see.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Hilary Mantel's three novels focusing on the life of Thomas Cromwell have probably shaped the views of many on the events and personalities of the Tudor court.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Learning from others is most often discussed in epistemology under the heading of 'testimonial knowledge,' a topic which has seen a great deal of philosophical attention in the last two decades.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "In fiction we do sometimes find a practice of outright assertion, or something close to it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "How might a fiction such as Ibsen's play provide reasons? In at least two ways.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "One is by providing an argument for some favored position, expressed by one or other character.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Another way opens up when the play transforms an abstract moral view into a concrete scenario that purports to show why this is the right position, or at least why it is a position worth taking seriously.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Fictions that remind us of these things can be epistemically valuable not because they change belief but because they help to connect belief more effectively to action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "We see now a variety of functions that a fictional work can fulfil in the learning process.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "One is simply to serve as the vehicle of expression for an idea.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Another is to provide reasons in favor of that idea, ones that are stated or implied by its characters.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "A third is to add persuasive power to the idea by rendering it concrete, showing how ideas and attitudes have practical consequences.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "On reflection however, it is not obvious that only real events can tell us anything informative.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "For example, we often want to know what might go wrong with some plan; waiting to find out what does go wrong gives us no way to avoid a potential disaster.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Instead, we try to construct an imaginative scenario-one that hasn't happened-which conforms to the plan but in which things do go wrong; that way we can revise the plan before it is too late.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "Fictions sometimes does this.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "We have focused so far on whether and how we can get knowledge from fiction.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "In at least two ways this may be too narrow a formulation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "First of all, the process of learning, where it focuses on belief, should surely have as its target the idea of belief improvement, and not every improvement in belief results in knowledge.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU31": {
      "text": "Encouraged by this thought we may see a close connection between fiction and skills, abilities and habits of various kinds.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU32": {
      "text": "The contributions of philosophers, critics, and literary theorists to the debate about learning from fiction have so far been notable for their lack of engagement with systematic empirical inquiry.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU33": {
      "text": "There is some evidence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU34": {
      "text": "But the search is at an early stage and there are difficulties in the way of getting the data we would most like to have.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU35": {
      "text": "Much current research exposes people to brief passages of fiction followed immediately by a battery of tests, whereas the claims traditionally made on behalf of fiction concern the cumulative benefits of extensive and varied reading.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU36": {
      "text": "Studies that addressed such claims directly would be costly in participants' time and commitment and would take decades to complete.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU37": {
      "text": "In recent years, there has been quite a lot of small-scale research into the effects of fiction, much of it focused on aspects of social cognition: our ability to understand and respond fluently to the thoughts, desires, and feelings of others.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU38": {
      "text": "Results have been mixed and in some cases only very small effects have been found.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU39": {
      "text": "Replication of some apparently positive results has been hard to achieve, and where improvements on empathy and ToM-related tasks have been found it is often unclear how long the results last.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU40": {
      "text": "Indeed, large and lasting effects on skills and abilities from one episode of reading would be surprising, so the current absence of strong evidence for a fiction-effect should not discourage researchers from conducting more fine-grained or more long-term studies.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
